Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Please join me in praying for all the passengers, crew members, military personnel, and families affected by the tragic collision between American Airlines Flight 5342 and a Black Hawk helicopter midair near Reagan National Airport last night.

While we work to get more information, we are grateful for the heroic efforts of the hundreds of first responders working throughout the night in the frigid waters of the Potomac River to continue their rescue operation.

American Airlines has confirmed that Flight 5342, traveling from ICT to DCA, carried 60 passengers and four crew members, while three soldiers were aboard the helicopter on a training mission. The U.S. Figure Skating Team has also confirmed that several skaters and coaches were on board the flight.

For those seeking information about loved ones who may have been on American Airlines Flight 5342, a hotline has been set up at 800-679-8215. May God bless everyone involved in this heartbreaking situation.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1835, Andrew Jackson became the first U.S. president to survive an assassination attempt. 

Richard Lawrence, an unemployed painter, tried to shoot Jackson as he was leaving a funeral at the Capitol. However, his gun misfired. Jackson, 67, responded by attacking Lawrence with his cane. During the struggle, Lawrence drew a second pistol, but it misfired as well. Jackson's aides then subdued Lawrence, leaving the president unharmed but shaken. 

Although Lawrence appeared mentally unstable and had no known political connections, Jackson believed his assassination attempt was orchestrated by his Whig Party opponents, who were at odds with him over his efforts to dismantle the Bank of the United States. 

Despite no evidence to support this claim, Jackson remained paranoid, and his vice president, Martin Van Buren, began carrying two loaded pistols for protection. Lawrence was committed to a mental institution, and later tests showed both of his pistols malfunctioned by chance, with the odds of such a misfire calculated at 1 in 125,000.

Name: Meuser, Daniel
text:
We are all deeply saddened by the tragic mid-air collision last night near Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport, involving an American Airlines flight from Wichita and a U.S. Army Black Hawk helicopter. This devastating accident resulted in the expected loss of all passengers and crew members on both aircraft.

Among those lost were U.S. Army pilots and members of the U.S. figure skating team, along with their families and coaches, who were returning home from a competition. As we learn more about this heartbreaking event, it is evident how profound this loss is for so many communities.

I extend my deepest condolences to the families who have lost loved ones. Our thoughts and prayers are with them this morning‚Äîprayers for the families of the passengers and soldiers, for all who were on board, and for the brave, hard-working first responders who spent the night in rescue and recovery efforts.

Preliminary reports indicate that both the helicopter and airplane were operating on standard aviation paths, suggesting this was a terrible accident.

As my good friend and colleague Rep. Ron Estes said, ‚Äúit is a real tragedy.‚Äù I am thankful to hear that the Kansas Congressional delegation is safe.

There will be discussions about improving and modernizing our transportation system to prevent future tragedies as air travel becomes more congested, but today is not that day. Today, we pray for the victims, their families, and all those affected. When the time comes, I look forward to working with Transportation Secretary Sean Duffy to bring our transportation system into the 21st century.

My office will continue to provide updates as more information becomes available. 

May God bless everyone impacted by this tragedy.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1950, President Harry S. Truman announced his decision to support the development of the hydrogen bomb, a weapon believed to be far more powerful than the atomic bombs dropped on Japan in World War II. 

This decision came after the Soviet Union detonated an atomic bomb, ending U.S. nuclear supremacy, and the discovery that Klaus Fuchs, a key scientist in the U.S. nuclear program, had been spying for the Soviets. These events, combined with the Soviets' knowledge of hydrogen bomb technology, led Truman to approve significant funding for the race to develop the first thermonuclear weapon.

In 1952, the U.S. successfully tested the hydrogen bomb, codenamed "Mike.‚Äù The 10.4-megaton bomb vaporized an island and created a crater over a mile wide. Its mushroom cloud reached 120,000 feet and spread 60 miles wide within half an hour. In 1955, the Soviet Union tested its own hydrogen bomb, marking the start of the nuclear arms race between the superpowers and the world‚Äôs first threat of thermonuclear war.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we shine a light on those who strengthen our community through their leadership, service, and dedication to uplifting others. Today, we recognize a remarkable woman whose passion for mentorship has opened doors for countless young people, empowering them to reach heights they never thought possible. Meet this week's Hometown Hero‚ÄîLeah Lovelace-Square, the 2025 Student Leader winner of the @Bucks_edu MLK Leadership Award.
 
A Guided Studies major at BCCC, Leah is pursuing concentrations in Management, Leadership, Entrepreneurship & Business, and Culture & Society‚Äîfields that perfectly reflect her commitment to developing future leaders and fostering opportunities for young people in our community.
 
Leah was raised in a military family and their journey took her across four states and three countries. At Baumholder American High School in Germany, she experienced firsthand the life-changing impact of mentorship and leadership programs. What began as an opportunity became a calling‚Äîto ensure every young person has access to guidance, empowerment, and the chance to build a future without limits.
 
Since 2010, Leah has dedicated herself to mentoring young people, helping them see beyond obstacles and dream beyond limitations. And, in 2022, she founded P.U.U.S.H. (Pushing Underprivileged, Underestimated Students Higher), offering faith-inspired awareness and development programs to enhance academic excitement, life-skill training, and leadership opportunities for students who might otherwise be left behind.
 
Through P.U.U.S.H., Leah is giving young people in our community a seat at the table and the skills and confidence to take the lead. By supporting and empowering young people, Leah is continuing the legacy of Dr. King and making a real difference in the lives of countless students and, in turn, strengthening our entire community. Her work is a testament to the power of belief, the importance of mentorship, and the profound truth that potential exists in every young person....sometimes, they just need a little push.
 
Please join me in celebrating Leah Lovelace-Square for her outstanding contributions and this well-deserved recognition as the MLK Leadership Student Leader Award recipient. On behalf of our entire community, we thank you, and we congratulate you!

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: While details are not clear, a blanket 25% tariff on *all* imports from Canada and Mexico would be bad news for Michigan. Here's why üßµ¬†https://t.co/PNmzLPYoJd

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: First, our auto industry and autoworkers. The U.S., Canada and Mexico are an integrated market ‚Äî no car made in Mexico or Canada is without U.S. parts, and no car made in Michigan is without parts from Canada and Mexico.¬†Parts can sometimes move across the border 3 or 4 times.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: So without some sort of carve-out for automakers, tariffs will hit nearly every car and make them more expensive ‚Äî with estimates as high as $6k per vehicle. Every Michigan auto company just lost sales. And every Michigan auto worker‚Äôs job is less secure.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: Canadian officials have also threatened to cut off energy exports from Ontario. About 1.5 million Michigan homes are powered by Canadian electricity ‚Äî and if Canada retaliates that can very quickly result in those 1.5 million homes paying more for electricity.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: Canada is the No. 1 export market for Michigan farmers. Canada has been clear they will retaliate with tariffs of their own ‚Äî and when they do, it will hit our farmers and ag exports first.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: Our farmers still haven‚Äôt made back market share from the first Trump Administration‚Äôs trade war with China, where our farmers had to be subsidized to cover lost revenue.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: And that‚Äôs just autos. Michigan‚Äôs farmers are also at risk.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: The bottom line here: Michigan builds things and grows things. That‚Äôs what we do. We‚Äôre a northern border state, and have built a beneficial trade relationship with Canada. These tariffs ‚Äî and the retaliation on US products ‚Äî threaten our auto industry and our food growers.

Name: Slotkin, Elissa
text: Tariffs should be used as a scalpel, not a sledgehammer.¬†I‚Äôm very much hoping for some clarification since hurting Michiganders is bad for everyone.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First 

Natakey Owens is a beacon of hope and strength in her community. As a licensed cosmetologist in Rocky Mount, North Carolina, she does more than style hair‚Äîshe provides guidance on family, faith, finances, and fitness. For over 26 years, she has built deep relationships with her clients, offering support that extends far beyond beauty.

But it‚Äôs her work outside the salon that truly defines her impact. After losing her mother, Pamela D. Page, to domestic violence, Natakey turned her pain into purpose, founding the Pamela D. Page Foundation to support survivors. The foundation provides advocacy, education, and therapeutic support through initiatives like the annual 5K walk/run, Life After Trauma Gala, and Hair & Fashion Show.

Beyond events, Natakey‚Äôs foundation hosts workshops, mental health fairs, and support programs for survivors and families. As a survivor herself, she knows the power of community and works tirelessly to create safe spaces for healing. In recognition of her impact, Natakey was honored with the 2025 Humanity Service Award from the City of Rocky Mount.

Thank you, Natakey, for your unwavering commitment to making a difference.

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Luna, Anna Paulina
text:
BREAKING: Rep. Luna Introduces RULES Act to Stop Asylum System Abuse

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

WASHINGTON, D.C.‚ÄîToday, Congresswoman Anna Paulina Luna (FL-13) introduced the House companion bill to the Refugees Using Legal Entry Safely (RULES) Act introduced by Senator Bernie Moreno (OH) earlier this year in the United States Senate. This bill seeks to amend the Immigration and Nationality Act to modify the eligibility requirements for asylum, thereby deterring and prohibiting the abuse of the system and ensuring its integrity.

‚ÄúThe days of open-border chaos are over. I‚Äôm joining Senator Moreno in introducing the RULES Act to put an end to the rampant fraud and abuse in our asylum system. America is a nation of law and order‚Äînot a free-for-all for illegal aliens gaming the system,‚Äù said Congresswoman Luna. ‚ÄúIf you want asylum in the greatest country on Earth, you follow our rules, period. No more loopholes, no more catch-and-release, no more second chances for lawbreakers. We are taking our border back.‚Äù

The introduction of the RULES Act in the House is a decisive step in strengthening the integrity of America‚Äôs asylum system. The bill establishes that the only way to claim asylum will be through a legal port of entry in the United States. Additionally, those applying cannot be released or paroled into the country before their cases are adjudicated. Additionally, individuals who have previously been denied asylum will not be able to reapply, and those who have entered the U.S. illegally in the past will be ineligible from applying for this most cherished humanitarian help.

Congresswoman Luna continues her fight to ensure the United States immigration system is under control and protects the interests of the American people.

Name: Collins, Susan M.
text:
The Maine economy is integrated with Canada, our most important trading partner. Certain tariffs will impose a significant burden on many families, manufacturers, the forest products industry, small businesses, lobstermen, and agricultural producers.

For example, 95 percent of the heating oil used by most Mainers to heat their homes comes from refineries in Canada. The Air National Guard Base in Bangor depends completely on jet fuel and diesel from Canada. From fisheries to potato farmers to paper mills, these tariffs will have a significant impact on Maine‚Äôs economy and risk increasing costs for our residents.

I am working with the Trump Administration to help its officials better understand the potential ramifications of certain tariffs on Maine and to find out more about their implementation, scope, duration, and other important information, including any exemptions they may make for northern border states, certain industries, agricultural producers, and others who rely on trade with Canada.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1917, Germany resumed unrestricted submarine warfare, a policy it had previously suspended due to pressure from the U.S. and neutral countries. 

This policy, initially introduced in 1915, declared the waters around the British Isles a war zone, where German U-boats would attack all merchant ships, including those from neutral nations. The sinking of the British Lusitania, which killed 1,201 people including 128 Americans, led to strong condemnation from the U.S. and a demand for Germany to cease attacking unarmed merchant vessels. 

Afterwards, Germany had limited U-boat attacks, but the navy continued to push for a more aggressive strategy. By early 1917, Germany's military leadership convinced Kaiser Wilhelm to approve resuming unrestricted submarine warfare, believing it could lead to victory by that fall. Despite opposition from the Chancellor, who feared antagonizing the U.S., the kaiser supported the decision, and he announced the resumption of unrestricted U-boat warfare, declaring Germany would "stake everything" and fight to the end.

Capt. Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Today, we bid a heartfelt farewell to Father Mike Davis, whose faithful leadership at Assumption BVM Parish in Feasterville since 2015 has uplifted and strengthened our entire community.

For over 38 years, Father Mike has been more than a pastor‚Äîhe has been a teacher, mentor, and Shepard, touching countless lives through his compassion, wisdom, and unwavering faith. His deep commitment extended beyond the parish, offering steadfast support to Lower Southampton‚Äôs first responders, comforting families in times of need, and fostering a true sense of belonging for all who crossed his path.

With his signature warmth, kindness, and dedication to serving others, he became a beloved pillar of our community over the past decade. While we will miss him dearly, we are grateful for his continued ministry as he begins his next chapter as Rector of Malvern Retreat House.

Please join me in thanking Father Mike and wishing him the best in his new journey ahead!

Name: Carter, Troy A.
text:
Please reflect on this famous poem, ‚ÄúFirst They Came‚Äù by Pastor Martin Niem√∂ller. He was a German Lutheran pastor who initially supported Hitler but later opposed the Nazi regime and was imprisoned in concentration camps.

Here is the most well-known version of the poem:

**‚ÄúFirst they came for the Socialists, and I did not speak out‚Äî
Because I was not a Socialist.

Then they came for the Trade Unionists, and I did not speak out‚Äî
Because I was not a Trade Unionist.

Then they came for the Jews, and I did not speak out‚Äî
Because I was not a Jew.

Then they came for me‚Äîand there was no one left to speak for me.‚Äù**

The message is clear: when injustice is ignored because it doesn‚Äôt personally affect someone, it will eventually grow until it does.

‚ÄîTAC

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1959, rock stars Buddy Holly, Ritchie Valens, and J.P. "The Big Bopper" Richardson, along with their pilot, died in a plane crash shortly after takeoff from Mason City, Iowa. 

The plane was en route to Moorhead, Minnesota, and investigators cited bad weather and pilot error as causes. Holly, whose band, The Crickets, had recently hit No. 1 with "That'll Be the Day," had chartered the plane due to bus troubles. Richardson, sick with the flu, convinced Waylon Jennings to give up his seat, and Valens won a coin toss for the remaining spot.

Buddy Holly, just 22, had been a rising star in rock and roll, his music influencing artists such as Bob Dylan and Paul McCartney. J.P. Richardson, 28, had found fame as a DJ and songwriter. Ritchie Valens, only 17, had already made an impact with songs like "La Bamba" and "Donna."

The tragedy was immortalized in Don McLean's 1972 song "American Pie," which referred to the day of the crash as "the day the music died."

Name: Mills, Cory
text:
On February 3, 1943, the U.S. Army Transport Dorchester was struck by an enemy torpedo. The transport carried over 900 service members; four Army Chaplains worked to get their soldiers out of danger and gave their own life jackets, making the ultimate sacrifice. When the ship began to sink, they went down together, arms linked and praying. May we never forget their sacrifice and continue to honor their legacy of selfless service.

Today, we honor the lives of the four Army chaplains who embodied true service and sacrifice. Four Chaplains Day remembers Lt. George L. Fox, Lt. Alexander D. Goode, Lt. Clark V. Poling, and Lt. John P. Washington for their sacrifice and heroism.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Congratulations to Hunter Stack of Troop 147 and Matthew Pienkowski of Troop 11 for achieving the rank of Eagle Scout‚Äîan honor that recognizes their leadership and dedication to our community.

For Hunter's project, he constructed two rehabilitation shelters for the Aark Wildlife Rehabilitation and Education Center in Chalfont. These shelters will provide a safe and secure environment for injured wildlife to heal before being returned to their natural habitat. His efforts strengthen local conservation initiatives and ensure that AARK can continue its mission of protecting and rehabilitating wildlife.

Matthew's project involved transforming an underutilized area at the Bensalem Senior Citizen Center Memorial Garden into a sanctuary for remembrance and reflection. By creating a space where families can gather, honor their loved ones with commemorative bricks, and hold celebrations of life, Matthew has provided the community with a venue that will offer comfort for years to come. Both projects serve as a testament to the idea that true leadership involves leaving things better than you found them.

I was also pleased to attend the Blue and Gold Scout Banquet Ceremonies in Morrisville and Bensalem today, where the next generation of Scouts are learning the same values of leadership and service that Hunter and Matthew have exemplified. It was inspiring to celebrate these young leaders, who will undoubtedly follow in their footsteps.

Join me in applauding Hunter, Matthew, and the Cub Packs and Boy Scout Troops of Morrisville and Bensalem ‚Äîthese outstanding future leaders of our community are truly commendable.

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
Without getting too deep in the constitutional weeds, Congress has several powers at its disposal, including:
  
üü¢ The power to spend.
üü¢ The power to investigate.
üü¢ The power to challenge actions in court.
üü¢ The power to impeach.

Let‚Äôs take them one at a time. (2/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
Amid the flurry of extreme actions taken by the Administration, there‚Äôs one question I keep hearing:

‚ÄúWhat are you going to *do* about it?‚Äù

It‚Äôs a fair point‚Äîespecially when the President has thus far avoided any real accountability.

I‚Äôll do my best to address it. (1/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
The Constitution is clear on Congress‚Äôs power of the purse. The Administration‚Äôs directive to ‚Äúimpound‚Äù funds from Congress is unconstitutional. While they rescinded a memo calling for a total freeze, they‚Äôre still stealing these funds.

We *will* fight them in the courts. (3/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
As for future court challenges: There are several ways to do this, like working w/ state AGs to challenge specific orders.

Last week, Maine‚Äôs AG joined colleagues in other states to sue the Administration, resulting in a temporary restraining order on the funding freeze.  (6/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
The courts will play a critical role, too. The President is pushing the boundaries of the separation of powers. The only remedy is to challenge him by getting the courts to rule he's gone too far.   

We‚Äôve already seen the courts block some of the Administration‚Äôs orders. (5/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
On investigations: 

The minority in Congress can‚Äôt control hearings or subpoenas. But we can call and question witnesses; work with whistleblowers to uncover vital information; and take our findings to the public.

All these tools are on the table. And we‚Äôll use them. (4/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
But there are things we *can‚Äôt* do on our own:

‚ùå Confirm or deny nominees.
‚ùå Stop POTUS from issuing crazy orders.
‚ùå Control which bills get voted on in the House.
‚ùå Impeach (more below).

Until we‚Äôre back in the majority, there‚Äôs only so much we can control. (8/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
On impeachment: Articles can be introduced by either party, but the majority decides whether they move forward. 

While this is an appealing option (we‚Äôve done it before‚Äîwhen we controlled the House), with Republicans in control, the chances of making it stick are nil. (9/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
But perhaps our most powerful tool is the ability to communicate with you‚Äîour constituents. To spell out, in plain terms, what‚Äôs really going on, and why it matters.

I take that responsibility seriously. And I know my colleagues do, too. (10/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
None of this is easy. We are in uncharted waters. But we *will* keep fighting the President‚Äôs actions as best we can‚Äîand we will use every tool at our disposal to keep this Administration in check.

We understand the stakes. And we‚Äôre not going to back down. (7/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text: I will always explain what I vote on and why. That's my job. But legislation in the Trump era is going to be different. There are a lot of ‚Äúgotcha‚Äù bills‚Äîones that have a sensible-sounding title but absolutely awful text (the Laken Riley Act is a great example of this). (11/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
Still, even a post or thread can help you better understand the details + stakes of bills I vote on (or the President‚Äôs actions).

But social media can‚Äôt be our only platform. Videos. Town halls. Media appearances. All are important.

Simply put: We need to be everywhere. (12/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
Because the more informed people are about this Administration‚Äôs unhinged actions, the more engaged‚Äîand enraged‚Äîthey become. And it‚Äôs that engagement and outrage that makes *our* words and actions so much more powerful.

Your voices really do matter. Keep using them! (13/14)

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
I know the past few weeks have been exhausting, and there is a long road ahead. We‚Äôll use the tools we have in Congress. We‚Äôll stand up + push back. We‚Äôll use our voices. 

And if the American people use theirs, too, we will be able to hold the Administration accountable. (14/14)

text:
Since coming to Congress, I‚Äôve made it my mission to fight for transparency and safety in the food and products we rely on. The truth is both alarming and unacceptable: ingredients banned across Europe and much of the world continue to be found in countless US foods, cosmetics, and household products, silently endangering American families. These toxic substances are fueling a crisis‚Äîlinked to a surge in chronic illnesses, developmental delays, and mental health challenges sweeping our nation. 
 
I am committed to this fight, and as part of that effort, I‚Äôve launched a new initiative‚ÄîThe Wellness Watch, a series dedicated to empowering families with the knowledge they need to make safer, healthier choices. 
 
This Week‚Äôs Focus: Paraquat‚Äîbanned in over 70 countries, this highly toxic pesticide is still widely used in the US, contaminating our food, water, and air. 
 
Americans deserve nothing less than transparency, accountability, and products that support‚Äînot harm‚Äîour health and well-being. The clock is ticking.

Following the chaos constructed by the Trump‚Äôs administration threat to freeze federal resources, I met with Dr. Gagan Pawar, CEO of Clinicas del Camino Real, Inc., to discuss the potential impacts of Trump‚Äôs flurry of executive actions, which targeted critical social services like Medi-Cal and local health centers. While the funding freeze has been rescinded, this administration has made it will stop at nothing to reduce funding for essential programs, putting millions at risk.

Clinicas provides vital care to our most vulnerable populations, and its mission relies heavily on stable federal support. Cuts to Medicaid and other essential services could force local health providers to scale back their operations or even turn away patients, further jeopardizing access to health care for those who need it most.

In #VenturaCounty alone, over 265,000 residents depend on Medi-Cal to access necessary healthcare. In California alone, over 14 million people rely on this program. Medi-Cal is not just health insurance‚Äì it‚Äôs a lifeline for children, working families, seniors, and people with disabilities.

In Congress, I will continue to fight for strong, consistent federal support for Medi-Cal and the critical programs andservices that protect Americans‚Äô health and well-being.

Name: Turner, Sylvester
text:
President Trump‚Äôs tariffs are nothing more than a hidden tax on hardworking families who are already struggling to make ends meet. These tariffs, essentially a Trump Tax, will raise the cost of food, housing, gas, and cars, all of which are essentials that families depend on every single day. 

For example, the price of groceries like avocados and maple syrup will go up. Building a home or buying a car will become more expensive. Even gas prices could rise because these tariffs disrupt supply chains. Families trying to get by will feel the squeeze, and for what? These tariffs do not protect American workers; they punish American consumers. What happened to helping the American people? These tariffs do the opposite. 

They make it harder for families to put food on the table, keep a roof over their heads, and afford basic transportation. This Trump Tax is not what voters expected or deserved. President Trump and his Republican allies need to stop ripping off hardworking taxpayers. Families need relief, not higher prices on everything they rely on just to live.

text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1789, George Washington was unanimously elected as the first president of the United States.

Washington's unanimous election came as no surprise. As the Revolutionary War's commander, he led the Continental Army to victory and, after the war, rejected calls to become a military dictator, instead retiring to Mount Vernon. When the Articles of Confederation proved ineffective, Washington returned to public life to preside over the Constitutional Convention and helped guide the creation of the presidency.

His legacy was summed up by his friend, Henry Lee: "First in war, first in peace, and first in the hearts of his countrymen."

Name: Bishop, Sanford D.
text: (1/6) Today, on what would be Rosa Parks' 112th birthday, we honor her legacy as a civil rights icon whose principled and steadfast leadership contributed to the fight for desegregation across the country.

Name: Bishop, Sanford D.
text: (2/6) This #BlackHistoryMonth, let us continue her fight for equity and justice, remember her legacy of nonviolent protest, and honor the legacies of those often-unsung heroes who helped to pave the way for a brighter day in the United States of America.

Name: Bishop, Sanford D.
text: (3/6) One of those unsung heroes was Mrs. Ola Mae Quarterman-Clemons. Ola Mae was born in 1944 in Worth County, Georgia. A product of the Dougherty County School System, she graduated from Monroe High School and went on to attend Albany State College (now University).

Name: Bishop, Sanford D.
text: (6/6) Following the Civil Rights Movement, Mrs. Quarterman, now dubbed ‚ÄúAlbany‚Äôs Rosa Parks,‚Äù lived a relatively quiet life until her passing in 2007 at the age of 64. #BHM2025

Name: Bishop, Sanford D.
text: (4/6) In January of 1962, she was asked to move to the back of a city bus at the request of the bus driver and refused saying, ‚ÄúI paid my d**n ten cents, and I'll sit where I please.‚Äù

Name: Bishop, Sanford D.
text: (5/6) She was subsequently arrested and spent 30 days in jail. Upon her release, she was expelled from Albany State and lost nearly everything she had. She immersed herself further into the Civil Rights Movement by organizing boycotts against the city‚Äôs transit system.

Name: Shaheen, Jeanne

Frederick Douglass, born around 1817, rose from the confines of slavery to become one of America‚Äôs most influential voices for liberty and equality.

Douglass not only taught himself how to read and write, but after escaping north, he used his talents as an orator and writer to expose the moral evil of slavery. Douglass‚Äô life and legacy serve as incredible examples of how faith, self-discipline and unshakable determination can transform both a life and a nation‚Äôs conscience.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text:
1/ USAID is an agency that saves lives, fights hunger, and strengthens democracy. It‚Äôs also an investment in the American people. 

Let‚Äôs talk about what USAID actually does‚Äîand why it makes America safer, stronger, and more respected in the world. üßµ

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 4/ USAID fights hunger. Feed the Future increases farmer self-sufficiency. Food for peace reduces hunger dramatically. Each package of USAID food is labeled ‚Äúfrom the American people.‚Äù Both programs are a display of our values and build goodwill around the world.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 3/ USAID helps fight diseases like malaria and AIDS. Since 2007, it has saved 6 million lives from malaria and helped 9.5 million people get HIV/AIDS treatment. Fighting disease abroad protects Americans at home from pandemics.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 6/ USAID strengthens economies that buy American goods. In 2016, it leveraged $892 million for small businesses, including $158 million for women entrepreneurs. Stronger economies mean more markets for U.S. exports and fewer economic migrants coming to the border.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 5/ USAID educates kids. Since 2011, it has helped 52 million kids go to school. Why does it matter? Education fights extremism. Every kid in school is at less risk of recruitment by terrorist groups, gangs, and cartels.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 7/ USAID leads disaster response, responding to chaos before it reaches us. From Ebola to earthquakes to conflicts around the world‚Äîwhen USAID helps to stabilize crises quickly, it prevents mass migration and security threats later on.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 9/ USAID helped lead the U.S. response to COVID-19. It provided $10.6 billion to fight the pandemic and get vaccines to the world. Stopping COVID abroad saved American lives and prevented economic collapse at home.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 8/ USAID defends democracy. Its Rule of Law programs help fight corruption, strengthen courts, and protect human rights. That means fewer authoritarian regimes and stronger U.S. allies.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 10/ At less than 1% of the federal budget, USAID makes America stronger, safer, and more prosperous. It is an investment of, by, and for the American people to fight hunger, disease, and instability before they become global crises that reach our shores.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 11/ It's also an agency that represents the best of our country. I'm proud of the work that employees at USAID do every day to stand up for human rights around the world. Not just because it is the smart thing to do, but because it is the right thing to do.
